@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "About this Site";
}

<div class="container bg-body-tertiary rounded p-4 mb-4">
    <h2>@ViewData["Title"]</h2>
</div>

<div class="container">
    <h4>History</h4>
    <p>
        In June of 2016, the Pathfinder team, a subset of the ExpressRoute PM team, started building two
        physical customer repro labs at Equinix in Seattle, WA (SE3) and Ashburn, VA (DC2). Creating,
        maintaining, and removing individual tenant environments, ensuring they were isolated, secure,
        and usable was a labor and time intensive, manual effort.
    </p>
    <p>
        To ease the burden of multiple configurations (Juniper, Cisco, PowerShell, Hyper-V, etc) a
        spreadsheet was created. Called the "Configuration Generator" it was a macro-based (vba) Excel
        spreadsheet.
    </p>
    <p>
        The spreadsheet was used to generate the Azure PowerShell and on-premises network device config
        and VM config needed to run multiple concurrent customer environments, called "Tenants". This
        worked well for a few years, until a more robust conversation was needed between Azure and the
        configuration generator. Things like dynamic IP addresses, or ER Direct Port S-Tags which are
        generated in Azure when the environments are created, were needed in the on-premises configuration.
        Given these addresses and tags are dynamically assigned at creation, a multi-step back and forth
        was needed to utilize this information. To avoid building REST handlers in VBA in Excel, it was
        decided to move this tool to a web based application where interacting with online services can
        happen natively from the Configuration Generation tool.
    </p>
    <p>
        This site is the web evolution of that spreadsheet.
    </p>
    <p>
        The site remained relatively unchanged — save for some PowerShell updates as Azure evolved — until
        early 2026, when "vibe coding" was put to the test and the site was rewritten, primarily from scratch,
        using Claude Opus 4.6 in GitHub Copilot in Visual Studio 2026. You can read more about the new site below!
    </p>

    <h4>Workflows</h4>

    <h5 class="mt-3">Lab Request Workflow</h5>
    <ol>
        <li>Any authenticated user submits a lab request via the <strong>Request a Lab</strong> form, specifying their ExpressRoute, VPN, VM, and region requirements.</li>
        <li>Admins (AuthLevel ≥ 8) see pending requests in the <strong>Admin → Tenant Requests</strong> queue, with a count badge on the nav menu.</li>
        <li>The reviewing admin selects a <strong>server preference</strong> (which determines the TenantID range and physical server assignment) and approves the request.</li>
        <li>On approval, a <strong>Tenant</strong> record is created in the database and the <strong>Logic App</strong> creates an ADO Experiment work item with the full tenant details and a discussion comment.</li>
        <li>The admin is redirected to the <strong>Tenant Edit</strong> page to review and refine settings. Saving edits updates both the database and the ADO work item.</li>
    </ol>

    <h5>Tenant Creation &amp; Environment Build Workflow</h5>
    <ol>
        <li>A <strong>Tenant</strong> record is created — either automatically when a lab request is approved, or manually by an admin (AuthLevel ≥ 8) via <strong>Admin → Create New Tenant</strong>.</li>
        <li>The admin reviews and refines the tenant settings on the <strong>Tenant Edit</strong> page — ExpressRoute, VPN, VM, addressing, and region configuration.</li>
        <li>The <strong>ConfigGenerator</strong> produces the full set of deployment artifacts for the tenant:
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Juniper configs</strong> — router configuration for ExpressRoute and VPN connectivity (MX/SRX)</li>
                <li><strong>Cisco configs</strong> — switch and router configuration for on-premises lab connectivity</li>
                <li><strong>PowerShell scripts</strong> — Azure deployment scripts for VNets, ExpressRoute circuits, gateways, VPN connections, and VMs</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li>The generated configs are deployed to build the environment:
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Azure</strong> — PowerShell scripts are executed to provision the Azure resources (VNets, circuits, gateways, VMs)</li>
                <li><strong>Servers</strong> — On-premises Hyper-V servers are configured with lab VMs using the generated VM specifications</li>
                <li><strong>Network Devices</strong> — Router and switch configurations are pushed to the lab network devices via SSH/NETCONF</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Once the environment is built and verified, an <strong>info email</strong> is sent to the requestor with connection details, credentials, and instructions for accessing their new lab environment.</li>
    </ol>

    <h4>Site Construction</h4>

    <h5 class="mt-3">Platform &amp; Hosting</h5>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Framework:</strong> ASP.NET Core (.NET 10) with C# 14, using Razor views and Bootstrap 5 styling with dark/light theme support.</li>
        <li><strong>Hosting:</strong> Azure App Service (Linux, West US 2) with Always On enabled to eliminate cold starts.</li>
        <li><strong>Custom Domain:</strong> <a href="https://www.pathlab.xyz" target="_blank">www.pathlab.xyz</a> with auto-renewing App Service Managed Certificate.</li>
        <li><strong>Database:</strong> Azure SQL Server (<code>labconfig.database.windows.net</code>) using Entity Framework Core 10 for data access.</li>
        <li><strong>Source Control:</strong> GitHub (<a href="https://github.com/tracsman/Projects" target="_blank">tracsman/Projects</a>) with GitHub Copilot-assisted development.</li>
    </ul>

    <h5>Authentication &amp; Authorization</h5>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Authentication:</strong> Microsoft Entra ID via Easy Auth (App Service platform-level authentication). No passwords or connection string secrets are stored anywhere in the application.</li>
        <li><strong>App Registration:</strong> Uses Federated Identity Credentials (FIC) with a user-assigned Managed Identity — no client secrets needed for Easy Auth.</li>
        <li><strong>SQL Authentication:</strong> System-assigned Managed Identity — the App Service identity is granted direct access to Azure SQL via Entra ID, eliminating the need for SQL credentials.</li>
        <li><strong>Local Development:</strong> Supports three auth modes — Easy Auth (App Service), code-based OIDC (with Entra ID app registration), or a fake development identity from <code>appsettings.Development.json</code>.</li>
        <li><strong>Authorization:</strong> Custom role-based system using a <code>Users</code> table with per-user AuthLevels (0–15). Each controller action checks the user's AuthLevel to determine access to features like tenant management, admin functions, and user administration.</li>
    </ul>

    <h5>Data Model</h5>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Tenants:</strong> Core entity representing a customer lab environment — includes ExpressRoute, VPN, VM, and addressing configuration for both Azure and on-premises resources.</li>
        <li><strong>Tenant Requests:</strong> Self-service lab request workflow — any authenticated user can submit a request, admins review and approve/reject from a queue.</li>
        <li><strong>Devices:</strong> Inventory of physical network devices (routers, firewalls, switches) in each lab location, with management IP addresses for SSH/NETCONF connectivity.</li>
        <li><strong>IP Addresses:</strong> Public IP address management and assignment tracking.</li>
        <li><strong>Config:</strong> Generated configuration data for each tenant (network device configs, PowerShell scripts).</li>
        <li><strong>FieldHelp:</strong> Tooltip help text for form fields — managed via the <strong>Admin → Tooltips</strong> page, displayed as <i class="bi bi-info-circle"></i> icons next to field labels on Request and Tenant forms.</li>
        <li><strong>Regions:</strong> Lookup table of Azure regions available for tenant deployments.</li>
        <li><strong>Settings:</strong> Application-level configuration values stored in the database.</li>
        <li><strong>Users:</strong> User directory with Ninja (admin) flags, display names, and AuthLevel assignments.</li>
    </ul>

    <h5>Key Services</h5>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>ConfigGenerator:</strong> The heart of the application — generates Juniper, Cisco, and PowerShell configuration scripts for each tenant based on their ExpressRoute, VPN, and VM settings. This is the web evolution of the original Excel/VBA "Configuration Generator" spreadsheet.</li>
        <li><strong>LogicAppService:</strong> Integrates with Azure DevOps via an Azure Logic App to create and update Experiment work items in the <code>msazure/One</code> ADO project. The web app sends tenant data to a Logic App HTTP trigger, which uses the built-in ADO connector (authenticated with Entra ID credentials) to manage work items. Discussion comments are added to track request approvals and tenant edits.</li>
        <li><strong>AuthLevelService:</strong> Resolves the authenticated user's email to their AuthLevel from the database on every request, injecting it into <code>HttpContext.Items</code> for use by controllers and views.</li>
        <li><strong>EasyAuthAuthenticationHandler:</strong> Custom authentication handler that reads Easy Auth platform headers (<code>X-MS-CLIENT-PRINCIPAL</code>) and constructs a <code>ClaimsPrincipal</code> with the user's name, email, and identity.</li>
        <li><strong>SshService:</strong> Provides SSH connectivity to on-premises network devices (routers, firewalls, switches) via the <code>SSH.NET</code> library. Credentials are retrieved at runtime from Azure Key Vault using the App Service Managed Identity — no passwords are stored in code or config. Connectivity is enabled by Regional VNet Integration, which routes outbound traffic from the App Service through the lab management VNet to on-premises devices via ExpressRoute. Features include:
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Run Command</strong> — send any CLI command to a device and view the output from the browser (<code>/Devices/RunCommand</code>).</li>
                <li><strong>OS Detection</strong> — automatically SSHes into all network devices, detects the platform from device naming conventions (Juniper MX/SRX, Cisco Nexus, Cisco ASR/ISR), runs the appropriate version command, parses the output, and updates the <code>OS</code> column in the database.</li>
                <li><strong>Config Sessions</strong> — interactive <code>ShellStream</code>-based SSH sessions for pushing config to devices. Juniper: <code>load set terminal</code> → <code>commit check</code> → <code>show | compare</code> → <code>commit and-quit</code>. Cisco: <code>configure terminal</code> → apply lines → <code>end</code> → <code>wr</code>.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>DbLoggerProvider:</strong> Custom <code>ILoggerProvider</code> that writes application log entries to the <code>AppLog</code> table in Azure SQL. Entries are buffered and flushed in batches every 5 seconds. Framework-level logs (ASP.NET Core, EF Core) are filtered out to keep signal-to-noise high. An admin log viewer (<code>/Logs</code>) provides level filtering, search, and pagination.</li>
    </ul>

    <h5>Azure DevOps Integration</h5>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Architecture:</strong> PathWeb → Azure Logic App (<code>PathWeb-ADO</code>) → Azure DevOps REST API. The Logic App acts as an authenticated proxy, using the built-in ADO connector with Entra ID credentials.</li>
        <li><strong>On Approval:</strong> Creates an Experiment work item in <code>msazure/One</code> with a full HTML description table of the tenant configuration. A discussion comment is added with the requester, request date, approver, and approval date. The returned WorkItemId is saved to the tenant record.</li>
        <li><strong>On Edit:</strong> Updates the existing work item's description and adds a discussion comment noting who made the change and when.</li>
        <li><strong>Work Item Links:</strong> The tenant Details page displays a clickable link to the ADO work item when a WorkItemId exists.</li>
    </ul>

    <h5>Deployment</h5>
    <ul>
        <li><strong><code>deploy-to-azure.ps1</code>:</strong> Full deployment script — creates the resource group, App Service Plan, Web App, binds the custom hostname with a managed SSL certificate, enables Managed Identity, configures Regional VNet Integration (for SSH/NETCONF access to on-premises devices), grants Key Vault Secrets User access for device credentials, configures Easy Auth with Entra ID (using FIC), sets up logging, builds, and deploys the application.</li>
        <li><strong><code>deploy-logic-app.ps1</code>:</strong> Deploys the <code>PathWeb-ADO</code> Logic App and Azure DevOps API connection. After deployment, the ADO connection must be authorized via the Azure Portal with Entra ID credentials.</li>
        <li><strong><code>quick-deploy.ps1</code>:</strong> Fast redeployment — skips all infrastructure provisioning, just builds, packages, deploys, and warms up the app (including EF Core JIT compilation and Razor page pre-compilation).</li>
        <li><strong><code>Warmup.ps1</code>:</strong> Post-restart warmup — polls the <code>/warmup</code> endpoint to pre-compile EF Core and the DI pipeline, then touches all Razor pages to force JIT compilation.</li>
        <li><strong>Health &amp; Diagnostics:</strong> <code>/health</code> and <code>/warmup</code> are excluded from Easy Auth so deployment and monitoring tools can reach them without authentication. <code>/diag</code> (authenticated) shows build info, environment, auth status, database connectivity, and tenant/request counts.</li>
        <li><strong>Application Initialization:</strong> <code>web.config</code> configures IIS Application Initialization to automatically hit <code>/warmup</code> before routing user traffic on deployments, scale-outs, and restarts — eliminating cold-start delays. The warmup endpoint pre-compiles EF Core query plans, populates the tooltip cache, and validates SQL connectivity.</li>
    </ul>

    <h5>NuGet Packages</h5>
    <ul>
        <li><code>Azure.Identity</code> — <code>DefaultAzureCredential</code> for passwordless auth to Azure SQL and Key Vault</li>
        <li><code>Azure.Security.KeyVault.Secrets</code> — retrieves device credentials from Azure Key Vault at runtime</li>
        <li><code>Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore</code> + <code>SqlServer</code> — ORM and Azure SQL provider</li>
        <li><code>Microsoft.Identity.Web</code> — Entra ID / OIDC authentication for local development</li>
        <li><code>SSH.NET</code> (Renci.SshNet) — SSH client library for connecting to on-premises network devices (CLI commands and NETCONF)</li>
    </ul>

